# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: child-labour-in-cocoa-production
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/a-place-at-the-table] Participant Media is the entertainment company behind the film, and it is distributed by Magnolia Pictures.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/a-place-at-the-table] The Participant/Magnolia team is also responsible for the film *Food, Inc.* (2008).
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/a-place-at-the-table] The film was originally titled *Finding North* but the name was later changed to *A Place at the Table*.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/a-place-at-the-table] As of 2012, about 50 million Americans were food insecure.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/a-place-at-the-table] This was approximately 1 in 6 of the overall population, with the proportion of children facing food insecurity even higher at about 1 in 4.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/a-place-at-the-table] One in every two children receive federal food assistance.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/a-place-at-the-table] Other Americans struggling with hunger are also featured, including a cop whose monthly paychecks only leaves him enough money to buy food for two weeks, forcing him to use a food bank.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/a-place-at-the-table] There is also a companion book titled *A Place at the Table: The Crisis of 49 Million Hungry Americans and How to Solve It,* edited by Peter Pringle and published by Public Affairs.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/a-place-at-the-table] The book features contributions from Jeff Bridges, Ken Cook, Marion Nestle, Bill Shore, Joel Berg, Robert Egger, Janet Poppendieck, David Beckmann, Mariana Chilton, Tom Colicchio, Jennifer Harris, Andy Fisher, Kelly Meyer and directors Kristi Jacobson and Lori Silverbush.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/a-place-at-the-table] The film was nominated for Grand Jury Prize at the 2012 Sundance Film Festival.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/a-place-at-the-table] At the 2013 IDA Documentary Awards, the film received the Pare Lorentz Award, which recognizes films for model filmmaking while focusing on the use of the natural environment, and justice for all and the illumination of pressing social problems.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/a-place-at-the-table] As of October 2015, it has a 90% approval ratings from 61 professional reviews aggregated by Rotten Tomatoes.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Aerated chocolate can be divided into four types.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] The most common, seen in Aero, has large bubbles and is produced under a vacuum, or by beating gas into liquid chocolate under pressure.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Aerated chocolate with tiny bubbles uses the same beating gas method but with nitrogen.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Aerated chocolates containing long tubes of air are extruded rather than moulded.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] The final type is an aerated chocolate with low fat content, held together by a skeleton of solid particles.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] They are made by first dissolving sugar, then forming an emulsion with other ingredients.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] It finally undergoes evaporation and drying or freeze drying to reduce the water content.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] In September 1935, British chocolate manufacturer Rowntree's brought the first aerated chocolate, Aero, to market.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] At the time, Rowntree's had been struggling for several years to compete with rival chocolate maker Cadbury's Cadbury Dairy Milk and was looking for a new product to gain an advantage.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] The new chocolate was the outcome of significant research focused on developing a "count line" chocolate inspired by the recent introduction of the Mars bar to the UK market.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Rowntree's patented their aerated chocolate broadly, covering variants such as chocolate with inclusions.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] As it was released to market, the new chocolate garnered strong sales and positive reviews, although some concerns were voiced within Rowntree's that the product would be a novelty.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] In their initial marketing, Rowntree's promoted aerated chocolate as better than solid chocolate: more digestible and lacking its "cloying after-taste".
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Further to their objections about aerated chocolate's digestibility, Cadbury contested the validity of the patent itself, arguing it overstepped and covered chocolates Cadbury already manufactured, as well as being malformed.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] In September 1936, Fry's released an aerated Crunchie bar made entirely of chocolate.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] They justified this move as not breaching the patent, saying it was not a block but a bar.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] As Aero sales began to dip, Rowntree's brought out variants, selling the first aerated chocolates with fruit and nut inclusions.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] After Fry's launched a second aerated chocolate in August 1937 called Ripple, Rowntree's had to decide whether they wanted to try to enforce their patent.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] By this time, Nestlé and Fry's had joined Cadbury in having expressed a willingness to challenge the patent in the courts despite it being officially approved by the patent office.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] On legal advice that there was a 50% likelihood of success in a court challenge, and the threat of court proceedings causing bad publicity, Rowntree's entered negotiations with other chocolate makers to discuss licensing aerated chocolate.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Rival companies were dominant in the proceedings dialogues, and Rowntree's ultimately agreed to licence aerated chocolate from June 1938 under the conditions that chocolate makers pay a sum with the release of new aerated chocolate lines and a 0.5% royalty on sales.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] After this agreement was put in place, Cadbury only released aerated chocolate products in overseas dominions where Aero was not established.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Nestlé-produced aerated chocolates included a chocolate called Bubblo, made in the UK for export to New Zealand under a New Zealand patent.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Aerated chocolate was already being sold in some overseas markets, by 1936 for instance, Aero was being successfully exported to Australia.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] The American chocolate maker Hershey's purchased the Aero patent the following May, later altering the flavour and texture for the American palate.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] During 1937, Rowntree's produced machinery for production in Ireland, Canada and South Africa, as well as for the companies Lindt and Van Houten.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] After production was temporarily paused in the UK during World War II, Aero returned to market, introducing aerated chocolate to a generation which had never seen the product, and by 1950 a product containing aerated chocolate coating wafers was released.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] The war also impacted production in Canada and South Africa.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Beginning in the late 1950s in an effort try to improve falling Aero sales, Rowntree's began releasing new varieties.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] These included coffee and orange varieties that were sold only briefly, but also included peppermint, which became a permanent fixture.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Marketing for these products abandoned the emphasis on aerated chocolate as a "unique" type of chocolate, instead focusing on the "bubbly" structure.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] In the 1970s, biscuit manufacturers began using micro-aeration to process chocolate for moulded products.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] This was a cost-saving measure: with less chocolate, the same volume of coated biscuit could be maintained.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] In 1981 or 1983, Cadbury released Wispa, an aerated chocolate with a more chunky shape than Aero bars, made using a secret, non-patented process.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] The launch of Wispa was successful, but it soon encountered manufacturing difficulties and was temporarily withdrawn from the market.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] While Wispa was off the market, Rowntree's developed and launched a chunky Aero which they successfully launched and was still being sold as of 2008.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Wispa was discontinued in the early 2000s so Cadbury could bring in a new aerated chocolate product aligned with the Cadbury Dairy Milk brand: Dairy Milk Bubbly.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Following an internet campaign in 2007, Cadbury reintroduced Wispa.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Today, Aero is manufactured by Nestlé, the brand having been acquired by Nestlé during a 1988 takeover of Rowntree's.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] As of 2023, other brands of aerated chocolate includes Mirage and Galaxy.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Aerated chocolate is a foam, meaning it contains gas, which conventional chocolate lacks.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] This distinction gives aerated chocolate different physical properties and eating experiences than regular chocolate: they have a lower density, occupying more space for the same weight, are more brittle, and have a larger surface area.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Chocolates held together by solid particles rather than fats have the lowest density among aerated chocolates, between 0.1–0.3 g/cm3 (0.058–0.17 oz/cu in), several times lower than the average density of regular chocolate (around 1.3 g/cm3 (0.75 oz/cu in)).
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] As a result of these properties, biting into some aerated chocolates, particularly those with larger bubbles, produces an audible crunch.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] When the chocolate enters the mouth, a "fragile" mouthfeel is created until the chocolate is chewed, upon which it quickly begins to melt and the mouthfeel shifts to become creamy.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] The way the chocolate melts changes with the size of bubbles: as they get smaller, the chocolate becomes smoother and melts quicker.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] In the fourth type of aerated chocolate, those held together by solid particle skeletons rather than with fat, the chocolate doesn't melt with heat as conventional chocolate does.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Rather, because of its very low density, as it enters the mouth it dissolves.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Aerated chocolates have a more intense flavour than conventional chocolates due to their larger surface area.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] The gas used to aerate chocolates also has an effect on the intensity of flavour, although a comparatively small one.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Although aerated chocolates are often perceived by consumers as having a lower calorie content than regular chocolate, this is unfounded as the calorific value of foods are measured in calories per gram.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Aerated chocolate containing large bubbles is produced via two methods.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] In the first, melted chocolate is put under a vacuum, where it foams up.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] As the chocolate cools, and the fats within the chocolate set, the foam structure remains.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Sometimes gases such as carbon dioxide are introduced into the mixture before it is placed under the vacuum.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Although the method easily permits inclusions such as nougat or nuts, the production is labor-intensive and difficult to keep hygienic.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] As a result, the second method is more frequently used: working gases into liquid, tempered chocolate under high pressure.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Carbon dioxide is mainly used, although others include nitrous oxide.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Air is avoided, as oxygen causes chocolate to become rancid.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Any gases that do not dissolve are dispersed as bubbles through the chocolate using a beater.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] As the chocolate is released from the high pressure conditions, the bubbles expand, foaming the product; through this, the amount of pressure directly impacts bubble size.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] The setting chocolate is deposited in a moulded shell, after which the set interior is capped with liquid tempered chocolate.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Factors that affect bubble size include qualities of chocolate, such as viscosity and the rate of setting.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] The ingredients used, such as emulsifiers and milk fats also impact bubble size; other factors include type of gas and how much pressure is applied.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Micro-aerated chocolate is created using the method of beating gases in under high pressure.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Unlike aerated chocolates produced with large bubbles, micro-aerated chocolate has nitrogen beaten into the mixture.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] The resulting chocolate, different not only in bubble size but also flavour and texture.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] This is theorised to arise from the gas having a different solubility.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] Aerated chocolates containing long tubes of air are also created using this technique, but their distinction comes from how the aerated chocolate is extruded rather than set in a moulded shell.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] The final type, those held together by a skeleton of solid particles, are produced using water evaporation methods.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] In the first of these, sugar is dissolved in water.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] This solution is emulsified with cocoa liquor and milk solids, which is evaporated and then dried using industrial machinery, until the product contains less than 2% water.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] In the second, water is emulsified with liquid chocolate and set and then freeze dried, removing the water.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] A major source of bubble instability is when a wide variety of sizes of bubbles are created, gases in smaller bubbles diffuses or disperses into larger bubbles.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] This is due to their differing Laplace pressures.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] As of 2023, technologies to control bubble size, distribution and movement were difficult to employ during production.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] "Advanced" research was underway, including by companies such as Nestlé.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] In 2013, scientists released the results of experimental research on the impact of phospholipids on aerating cocoa butter.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] The research found that although all phospholipids tested made cocoa butter foam more, the foam's stability varied by type of phospholipid.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/aerated-chocolate] The final cocoa butter was also observed to be more stable when the process was undertaken at lower temperatures.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] An **agricultural cooperative**, also known as a **farmers' co-op**, is a producer cooperative in which farmers pool their resources in certain areas of activities.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Agricultural production cooperatives include collective farms in former socialist countries, the kibbutzim in Israel, collectively-governed community shared agriculture, Longo Maï cooperatives in Costa Rica, France, and some other countries, CPAs in Cuba, and Nicaraguan production cooperatives.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] In Southeast Asian developing countries such as Vietnam, agricultural cooperatives remain to play an important role in economic and social activities in rural areas, although they have relied mainly on government subsidies .
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Notable examples of agricultural cooperatives include Dairy Farmers Of America, the largest dairy company in the US, Amul, the largest food product marketing organization in India, and Zen-Noah, a federation of agricultural cooperatives that handles 70% of the sales of chemical fertilizers in Japan.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Agricultural cooperatives are owned and democratically controlled by their members.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] The governance structure can vary between the different types, but in general members elect representatives to a board of directors and contribute to organizational decision making through a democratic voting process.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] During the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries in certain areas of Greece, back then, under Ottoman rule, a particular form of cooperative organization was developed.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Networks of adjacent rural communities were organized as a local production system designed to produce specific agricultural or craft products which were then destined for international markets.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Derived from the Byzantine guilds, they were enabling better control of the production and tax collection by the Ottoman administration.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] One of the first cooperatives was the Rochdale Society, formed in 1844 in Rochdale, England.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] The Society's first enterprise was a retail store, but it very soon also established a corn mill.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] The first agricultural cooperatives were created also in Europe in the second half of the nineteenth century.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] They spread later to North America and the other continents.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] They have become one of the tools of agricultural development in emerging countries.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Farmers also cooperated to form mutual farm insurance societies.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] They were created in the same periods, with the initial purpose of offering farm loans.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Some became universal banks such as Crédit Agricole or Rabobank.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Cooperatives as a form of business organization are distinct from the more common investor-owned firms (IOFs).
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Both are organized as corporations, but IOFs pursue profit maximization objectives, whereas cooperatives strive to maximize the benefits they generate for their members (which usually involves zero-profit operation).
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] The former situations are characterized in economic theory as market failure or missing services motive.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] The latter drive the creation of cooperatives as a competitive yardstick or as a means of allowing farmers to build countervailing market power to oppose the IOFs.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] The concept of competitive yardstick implies that farmers, faced with an unsatisfactory performance by IOFs, may form a cooperative firm whose purpose is to force the IOFs, through competition, to improve their service to farmers.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] A practical motivation for the creation of agricultural cooperatives is related to the ability of farmers to pool production and/or resources.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] In many situations within agriculture, it is simply too expensive for farmers to manufacture products or undertake a service.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Cooperatives provide a method for farmers to join in an 'association', through which a group of farmers can acquire a better outcome, typically financial, than by going alone.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] This approach is aligned to the concept of economies of scale and can also be related as a form of economic synergy, where "two or more agents working together to produce a result not obtainable by any of the agents independently".
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] While economic benefits are a strong driver for forming cooperatives, they are not the only consideration.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Similar economic advantages can also be achieved through other organizational forms, such as IOFs.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] A key advantage of the cooperative model for farmers is that they retain governance over the association, ensuring that ownership and control remain with the members.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] This structure means that profit distributions—whether through dividends or patronage rebates—are shared exclusively among farmer-members, rather than external shareholders as in IOFs.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Agricultural cooperatives play a critical role in rural socio-economic development, food security, and poverty alleviation, particularly in regions where agriculture is the main source of employment and income.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] These cooperatives provide smallholder farmers with access to resources, education, tools, and markets that might otherwise be inaccessible.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] By organizing into producer cooperatives, farmers can also increase their resilience to economic and environmental shocks.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] These organizations help build the capacity of smallholders to adapt to challenges in ways that reduce vulnerability and enhance long-term sustainability.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Some studies suggest that membership in a producer organization is more strongly correlated with improved farm output or income than other interventions, such as technical training, certification, or credit alone.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] In agriculture, there are broadly three types of cooperatives: a manufacturing/marketing cooperative, a purchasing/supply cooperative, and a service cooperative.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Agricultural marketing cooperatives are cooperative businesses owned by farmers, that market, process, package, and distribute members' agricultural products.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] By pooling production, marketing cooperatives enable farmers to increase bargaining power and participate in markets that would be difficult for individual farmers to enter.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Marketing cooperatives may also provide value added processing and other services to increase benefits to the members.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Agricultural supply cooperatives aggregate purchases, storage, and distribution of farm inputs for their members.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] By taking advantage of volume discounts and utilizing other economies of scale, supply cooperatives bring down the cost of the inputs that the members purchase from the cooperative compared with direct purchases from commercial suppliers.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Supply cooperatives provide inputs required for agricultural production, including seeds, fertilizers, chemicals, fuel, and farm machinery.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Some supply cooperatives operate machinery pools that provide mechanical field services (e.g., plowing, harvesting) to their members.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Agricultural service cooperatives provide members with services that support agricultural production.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] These services might include product transportation, storage, credit, electricity, technical assistance, and veterinary care.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Similar to supply cooperatives, service cooperatives pool members’ resources to improve access to affordable, reliable, and high-quality services that individual producers may not be able to afford on their own.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Agricultural cooperatives are governed by their farmer members through a democratically elected board of directors.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] The board establishes the cooperative's strategic direction and oversees the hired management.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Hired management is responsible for the day to day operations.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Agricultural supply cooperatives have historically played a very important role in American agricultural history.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Supply cooperatives allow farmers to collectively purchase inputs such as seed, feed, fertilizer, fuel, livestock, and farm equipment.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Department of Agriculture (USDA), agricultural cooperatives reported a balance sheet of approximately $125.6 billion USD in 2024.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Although consolidation within the agricultural sector has reduced the number of cooperatives in recent years, supply cooperatives continue to provide access to quality and accessible agricultural inputs for producers.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Current examples include Grange Cooperative, founded in Oregon in 1939, and Southern States Cooperative, founded in Virginia in 1923.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Both cooperatives help farmers obtain quality seed, and other agricultural inputs catered to the needs of farmers in their respective regions.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] New Zealand has a strong history of agricultural cooperatives, dating back to the late 19th century.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] The first was the small Otago Peninsula Co-operative Cheese Factory Co.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Ltd, started in 1871 at Highcliff on the Otago Peninsula.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] With active support by the New Zealand government, and small cooperatives being suitable in isolated areas, cooperatives quickly began to dominate the industry.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] By 1905, dairy cooperatives were the main organisational structure in the industry.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] In the 1920s–'30s, there were around 500 co-operative dairy companies compared to less than 70 that were privately owned.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] However, after World War II, with the advent of improved transportation, processing technologies and energy systems, a trend to merge dairy cooperatives occurred.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] By the late 1990s, there were two major cooperatives: the Waikato-based New Zealand Dairy Group and the Taranaki-based Kiwi Co-operative Dairies.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] In 2001 these two cooperatives, together with the New Zealand Dairy Board, merged to form Fonterra.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] This mega-merger was supported by the New Zealand Government as part of broader dairy industry deregulation, which allowed other companies to directly export dairy products.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Two smaller cooperatives did not join Fonterra, preferring to remain independent – the Morrinsville-based Tatua Dairy Company and Westland Milk Products on the West Coast of the South Island.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] The other main agricultural co-operatives in New Zealand are in the meat and fertiliser industries.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] The meat industry, which has struggled at times, has proposed various mergers similar to the creation of Fonterra; however, these have failed to gain the necessary member support.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] In Canada, the most important cooperatives of this kind were the wheat pools.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] These farmer-owned cooperatives bought and transported grain throughout Western Canada.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] They replaced the earlier privately and often foreign-owned grain buyers and came to dominate the market in the post-war period.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] By the 1990s, most had demutualized (privatized), and several mergers occurred.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Now all the former wheat pools are part of the Viterra corporation.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] The Amazon region of Ecuador is known for producing world-renowned cacao beans.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] In the Napo region 850 Kichwa families have come together with help from American biologist, Judy Logback, to form an agricultural marketing cooperatives, Kallari Association.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] This cooperative has helped increase benefits for the families involved as well as to protect and defend their Kichwa culture and the Amazon rainforest.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] In India, there are networks of cooperatives at the local, regional, state and national levels that assist in agricultural marketing.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] The commodities that are mostly handled are food grains, jute, cotton, sugar, milk and nuts.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Dairy farming based on the Anand Pattern, with a single marketing cooperative, is India's largest self-sustaining industry and its largest rural employment provider.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Successful implementation of the Anand model has made India the world's largest milk producer.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Small-scale farmers with a few heads of milch cattle deposit milk into the village union's collection points twice daily, and the milk is then processed at district unions.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] After this, it is marketed by the state cooperative federation nationally under the Amul brand name, India's largest food brand.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Under this model, three-fourths of the price paid by the primarily urban consumers goes into the hands of millions of small dairy farmers.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Production of sugar from sugarcane mostly takes place at cooperative sugar cane mills owned by local farmers.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] The shareholders include all farmers, small and large, supplying sugarcane to the mill.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Over the last sixty years, the local sugar mills have played a crucial part in encouraging rural political participation and as a stepping stone for aspiring politicians.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] This is particularly true in the state of Maharashtra where a large number of politicians belonging to the Congress party or NCP had ties to sugar cooperatives from their respective local areas.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Mismanagement and manipulation of the cooperative principles have made a number of these operations inefficient.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] By pooling production, marketing cooperatives allow farmers to market their products collectively, access transportation infrastructure, storage and participate in larger markets that would be inaccessible if they were selling individually.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] To meet the needs of their members, marketing cooperatives often provide additional services including processing, packaging, logistics, quality control, and market research.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] According to the USDA, there were 830 marketing cooperatives operating in the United States in 2024.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] Dairy cooperatives are one of the most significant agricultural marketing cooperatives in the United States.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] These cooperatives market milk on behalf of their members, operate processing facilities, and help farmers manage price fluctuations in the dairy industry.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/agricultural-cooperative] According to the USDA, dairy cooperatives marketed approximately 167 billion pounds of milk in 2017, representing 77.8 percent of all milk marketed in the by the nation's farmers.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The **American University** (**AU** or **American**) is a private federally chartered research university in Washington, D.C., United States.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Its main campus spans 90 acres (36 ha) on Ward Circle, in the Spring Valley and Tenleytown neighborhoods of Northwest D.C.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] American was chartered by an Act of Congress in 1893 at the urging of Methodist bishop John Fletcher Hurst, who sought to create an institution that promoted public service, internationalism, and pragmatic idealism.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The university was founded by the General Conference of the Methodist Episcopal Church as a national Methodist institution.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] It remains affiliated with the United Methodist Church, however, religious affiliation is not a criterion for admission, employment, nor an academic requirement.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] AU broke ground in 1902, opened as a graduate education institution in 1914, and admitted its first undergraduates in 1925.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] AU consists of eight schools and colleges: the School of International Service; the College of Arts and Sciences; the Kogod School of Business; the School of Communication; the School of Professional and Extended Studies; the School of Public Affairs; the Linda A. and H.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Kent Baker School of Education; and the Washington College of Law (WCL).
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] American offers over 160 academic programs, including 71 bachelor's degrees, 87 master's degrees, and 10 doctoral degrees, as well as JD, LLM, and SJD programs.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The university is classified as an "R1: Doctoral Universities – Very high research activity".
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] With a student body of over 13,000 representing all 50 U.S. states and 141 countries, nearly a fifth of the students are international.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Student athletes compete in intercollegiate athletic teams as the American Eagles in the NCAA Division I as a member of the Patriot League.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] AU is home to The Jack I. and Dorothy G.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Bender Library, which holds more than one million books and is part of the Washington Research Library Consortium, along with WCL's Pence Law Library.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] American is one of the top three feeder schools to the U.S.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] American University was established in the District of Columbia by an Act of Congress on December 5, 1892, primarily due to the efforts of Methodist bishop John Fletcher Hurst, who aimed to create an institution that could train future public servants.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Hurst also chose the university's site, which was in the rural periphery of Washington, D.C.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] After more than three decades devoted principally to securing financial support, the university was officially dedicated on May 15, 1914.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Instruction began in October 1914 with 28 student enrollees, 19 of whom were graduates and the remainder special students not candidates for a degree.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] American University's first commencement was held on June 2, 1915.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] During World War I, the university allowed the U.S. military to use the university's grounds for testing.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In 1917, the U.S. military divided American University into two segments: Camp Leach and Camp American University.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Camp Leach was home to advanced research, development, and testing of modern camouflage techniques.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Camp American University was an experiment station that became the birthplace of the United States' chemical weapons program and the site of chemical weapons testing.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] A major cleanup effort began in the 1990s to remove chemical weapon remnants, particularly a cache of over 200 mustard-gas shells buried beneath the campus.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Additional material was located in June 2024.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Instruction was first offered at only the graduate level, in accordance with the vision of the university's founders.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] This changed in 1925 with the establishment of the College of Liberal Arts (subsequently named the College of Arts and Sciences), which offered undergraduate degrees and programs.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] What is now the School of Public Affairs was founded in 1934, partly to educate future federal employees in public administration.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] AU's relationship with the U.S. government continued during World War II, when the campus hosted the U.S.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Navy Bomb Disposal School and a WAVE barracks.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] For AU's role in these wartime efforts, the Victory ship SS *American Victory* was named in its honor.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The post-World War II-period saw considerable growth and restructuring of AU.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In 1949, the university merged with the Washington College of Law, which had been founded in 1896.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Shortly after that, three departments were reorganized as schools: the School of Business Administration in 1955 (subsequently named the Robert P. and Arlene R.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Kogod College of Business Administration and in 1999, renamed the Kogod School of Business); the School of Government and Public Administration in 1957; and the School of International Service in 1958.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In the early 1960s, the Department of Defense and the Central Intelligence Agency operated the federally funded research and development center (FFRDC) Special Operations Research Office as a think-tank at American University.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] AU's political involvement was furthered by President John F.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Kennedy's Spring 1963 commencement address.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In the speech, Kennedy called on the Soviet Union to work with the United States to achieve a nuclear-test-ban treaty and to reduce the considerable international tensions and the specter of nuclear war during that juncture of the Cold War.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] From 1965 to 1977, the College of Continuing Education existed as a degree-granting college responsible for on- and off-campus adult-education programs.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The Lucy Webb Hayes School of Nursing provided an undergraduate study in Nursing from 1965 until 1988.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The university bought the Immaculata Campus in 1986 to alleviate space problems.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In 1986, construction on the Adnan Khashoggi Sports and Convocation Center began.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Financed with $5 million from and named for Saudi Arabian Trustee Adnan Khashoggi, the building was intended to update athletics facilities and provide a new arena, as well as a parking garage and office space for administrative services.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Costing an estimated $19 million, the building represented the largest construction project to date but met protest by both faculty and students to the university's use of Khashoggi's name on the building due to his involvement in the international arms trade.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In 1988, the College of Public and International Affairs was reorganized to create two free-standing schools: the School of International Service and the School of Public Affairs, incorporating the School of Government and Public Administration and the School of Justice.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] That same year, construction of the Adnan Khashoggi Sports Center was completed while the Iran–Contra Affair controversy was at its height, although his name remained on the building until after Khashoggi defaulted on his donation obligation in the mid-to-late 1990s.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In 1997, American University of Sharjah, the only coeducational, liberal arts university in the United Arab Emirates, signed a two-year contract with AU to provide academic management.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] This contract has since been extended multiple times through August 2009.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] A team of senior AU administrators relocated to Sharjah to assist in the establishment of the university and guide it through the Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools accreditation process.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In fall 2005, the Katzen Arts Center and American University Museum opened, funded by a donation from Washington, D.C. philanthropists Dr.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The center continues to exhibit the Katzen's art collection and focuses on interdisciplinary collaboration in the arts.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Benjamin Ladner was suspended from his position as president of the university on August 24, 2005, pending an investigation into possible misuse of university funds.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] University faculty passed votes of no confidence in President Ladner the following month.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] One month after the faculty vote, the board of trustees decided that Ladner would not return to American University as its president.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] According to *The Chronicle of Higher Education*, Ladner would receive total compensation of $4,270,665 in his final year of service, the second-highest of any university president in the nation.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Kerwin, a long-time AU administrator, was then appointed interim president.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] On September 1, 2007, Kerwin was appointed to the position permanently after two applicants declined an offer from the board of trustees.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Ground was broken for the new School of International Service building on November 14, 2007, and completed in 2010.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] At the building's opening, a speech was given by then-Hawaiian Senator Daniel K.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In 2015, American University began offering an accredited, accelerated online MBA program.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In May 2017, Kerwin retired as AU's president.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In June, shortly after leaving her position as HHS secretary, Sylvia Mathews Burwell was tapped to become the 15th president and the first woman to serve in that role.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In 2017, Taylor Dumpson became AU's first Black female student body president.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In her first full day in office, bananas were found at three places on campus, hanging from noose-like ropes, and marked with the initials "AKA," the initials of the Alpha Kappa Alpha sorority.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In 2019, the School of Education (SOE) was separated from the College of Arts and Sciences (CAS).
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] According to then dean of SOE Cheryl Holcomb-McCoy the move was made to "encourage more students to pursue careers in education." Areas of study that students can pursue within the school include: teacher education, special education, education policy and leadership, and international education.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The school is home to the Institute for Innovation in Education and the Center for Postsecondary Readiness and Success.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] On April 22, 2020, AU announced that it had divested its endowment of fossil fuels, becoming one of the first universities in the United States to completely divest of both direct and indirect fossil fuel holdings.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Following a student referendum in favor of divestment, the AU board of trustees voted against divesting the endowment in 2014.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The decision to divest in 2020 came after extensive student campaigning from groups like Fossil Free AU and the undergraduate student government.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In 2020, Fossil Free AU pushed for a second student referendum on the subject, and the student government released a report on divestment, presented to the board of trustees by student comptroller Robert Zitzmann.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In early August 2023, Burwell announced she would be stepping down as AU's 15th president but would continue work in AU's Sine Institute for Policy and Politics.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] On July 1, 2024, Jonathan Alger became AU's 16th president.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Alger named Matthew Eynon, former Associate Vice President of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT), to lead AU's University Advancement and Strategic Planning.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In November 2024, it was reported that AU was considering restructuring its SOE, potentially merging it back into the CAS or even dissolving the SOE altogether, due to budget concerns.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In February 2025, longtime finance professor H.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Kent Baker made an undisclosed donation, the largest individual gift in AU's history, in honor of his late wife, Linda.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The Board of Trustees recognized his transformative gift by renaming the school the Linda A. and H.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Kent Baker School of Education, a move that ultimately preserved the school's independent status.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In May 2026, Alger announced his resignation as AU's 16th president.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Beginning in July 2026, David Marchick serves AU as interim president until the next president is in place.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] American University has two contiguous campuses for academics and student housing: the main campus on Massachusetts Avenue and the East Campus on Nebraska Avenue.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Washington College of Law was moved to the site of the Tenley Campus located in nearby Tenleytown.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] AU owns several other buildings in Tenleytown, Spring Valley, East Campus in Wesley Heights, and American University Park areas.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The first design for the campus was done by Frederick Law Olmsted.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] However, it was significantly modified over time due to financial constraints.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The campus occupies 84 acres (340,000 m2) adjacent to Ward Circle, the intersection of Nebraska and Massachusetts Avenues.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] AU's campus is predominantly surrounded by the affluent residential neighborhoods characteristic of the Northwest quadrant of Washington, D.C.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The campus includes a main quadrangle surrounded by academic buildings, nine residential halls, a 5,000-seat arena, and an outdoor amphitheater.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The campus has been designated a public garden and arboretum by the American Public Gardens Association, which includes several exotic plantings dotting the landscape.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Tenley Campus, formerly the all-girls Immaculata Preparatory School, is located half a mile east of American's main campus.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The university purchased the property in 1987 to serve as a satellite campus and to host the Washington Semester program.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Since 2016, Tenley Campus has housed the American University Washington College of Law (WCL).
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Over the years, several dormitory halls and academic buildings were renovated or replaced with modern facilities to accommodate the needs of a law school.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] As of the Class of 2023, 75% of WCL graduates secured jobs requiring bar passage immediately after graduation.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Additionally, 82% of graduates obtained employment that either required bar passage or considered a Juris Doctor degree an advantage.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Only twenty students still sought employment post-graduation.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The university is composed of eight divisions, referred to as colleges or schools, which house its academic programs.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Except for WCL, undergraduate and graduate courses are housed within the same division, although organized into different programs.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Admission to American is considered to be "more selective" by the *U.S.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] For the Class of 2027 (enrolling fall 2023), AU received 17,786 freshmen applications; 8,427 were admitted (47%) and 1,856 enrolled.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The middle 50% range of SAT scores were 670–740 for Evidence-Based Reading and Writing and 620–710 for Math.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The middle 50% range of the ACT Composite score was 29–32.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] News & World Report* ranked American University 4th in study abroad programs.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] American University operates three premier programs in Brussels, Belgium; Madrid, Spain; and Nairobi, Kenya but, also partners with universities across the globe.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] American University's undergraduate program was tied for 91st overall among "national universities" in *U.S.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] News & World Report*'s 2025 rankings, tied for 26th in "Best Undergraduate Teaching", 38th in "Most Innovative Schools", and 114th in "Best Value Schools".
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In 2008, 2010, 2012, and 2018, American University was named the most politically active school in the nation by *The Princeton Review'*s annual survey of college students.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In 2006, the *Fiske Guide to Colleges* ranked AU as a "Best Buy" college for the quality of academic offerings in relation to the cost of attendance.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] However, in 2013, the Daily Beast listed the school in their list of "20 Least Affordable Colleges".
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] For two years in a row, American University has had more students chosen to receive Presidential Management Fellowships than any other college or university in the country.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In spring 2006, 34 graduate and law students were chosen for the honor.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] American University routinely ranks among the top mid-sized universities for producing Peace Corps volunteers.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The School of Public Affairs is ranked 9th in the U.S. by *U.S.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] On September 24, 2018, AU President Sylvia M.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Burwell announced the **Sine Institute of Policy and Politics**.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Taking advantage of AU's location in the nation's capital, the institute aims to bring together scholars, journalists, and experts from the public, private, and nonprofit sectors to find common ground and bipartisan policy solutions to the nation's problems.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The Sine Institute launched with a conversation between Burwell and Republican Senator Bob Corker of Tennessee.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Bender Library and Learning Resources Center is the main library facility for the campus.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The University Library is part of the Washington Research Library Consortium (WRLC), which includes seven other libraries.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The WRLC operates a consortium loan service between member institutions and has a shared collections site in Upper Marlboro, Maryland.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The Library's Archives and Special Collections houses unique and rare materials and information on the institution's history.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The University Archives is the repository for papers and other documents, including sound recordings and photographs, spanning more than a century of the university's history.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Special Collections houses rare materials.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] AU has over 150 recognized organizations on campus, ranging from political to social.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] American has a Model United Nations team, ranked 1st in North America since the 2021–2022 academic year.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The team competes actively at intercollegiate tournaments, and also hosts "AmeriMUNC" (American Model United Nations Conference) a yearly High School Model UN competition on campus.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] American University Student Government (AUSG) is the governing body of the student population and has been ranked as the most active student government in the United States.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] It comprises the Undergraduate Senate and the Executive Branch.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] AUSG promotes advocacy and launches initiatives on campus supported by the student body.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] AU has eight student-run university-recognized media organizations, including *The Eagle* newspaper, radio station WVAU, the Second District Records record label, the American Literary Magazine (AmLit), and several magazines.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] These media organizations are governed by a Student Media Board and are funded through the university's undergraduate student activity fee.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The university also owns National Public Radio's flagship capital affiliate, WAMU, which has been a source of nationally and internationally distributed programming such as *The Diane Rehm Show* and *1A*.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] While AU is affiliated with the United Methodist Church and hosts the AU United Methodist Community, AU has a variety of other religious life groups, including Catholic, Chabad Lubavitch of the AU Community, American University Hillel, and the Jewish Student Association.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] There are also several independent organizations.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] An environmental science class at American conducted a study from February to April 2009 to measure the amount of food waste avoided by eliminating trays from one of the college's dining halls.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] The class found that trayless dinners resulted in 47.1% less solid waste than dinners during which trays were used, spurring a student-driven campaign to go trayless across campus.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In 2011, the Association for the Advancement of Sustainability in Higher Education (AASHE) awarded American University a gold rating, the highest possible, on their STARS scale for sustainability.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Since then, American University has earned five consecutive gold ratings, the most recent in 2020.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Also in 2011, American University's School of International Service building earned Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) Gold certification for its 70,000 square foot building renowned for sustainable design and "cradle-to-cradle" philosophy.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In 2014, American University ranked #2 in the Sierra Club's list of the 'Top 10 Greenest Colleges'.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In 2014, the university announced an ambitious project to build a solar farm in partnership with George Washington University.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] As of January 2016, the completed solar farm provides an equivalent of 50% of the university's electricity.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In 2018, American University became the first university in the United States to achieve carbon-neutral status.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] In 2020, AU announced that it had eliminated all public fossil fuel investments from its endowment.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] A member of the Patriot League, AU has several sports teams including men's and women's basketball, soccer, cross-country, swimming and diving, track, women's volleyball, field hockey, and lacrosse, and men's wrestling.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Club sports, such as tennis, rugby, rowing, ice hockey, field hockey, equestrian and ultimate frisbee also have teams.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Bender Arena, a multi-purpose facility, hosts many of American's athletic competitions.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Bender Arena opened on January 23, 1988, when AU's women's basketball team hosted James Madison University.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Reeves Field, home to AU's soccer team, earned the 2002 College Soccer Field of the Year by the Sports Turf Managers Association, hosted its fifth NCAA Tournament game, and served as the training site for the Uruguay national football team.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Reeves Field features a six-lane track to accommodate the track and field programs at AU and functions as a multi-purpose event site.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] American University has seven tennis courts and two basketball courts in the outdoor recreational facility located next to Reeves Field and behind Bender Arena.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] AU has hosted Patriot League tennis team championships three times since joining the league.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Both the men's and women's tennis teams have been cut from the athletics program.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] On March 14, 2008, AU earned its first NCAA tournament berth in men's basketball by defeating Colgate University in the Patriot League Championship Game.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] However, AU lost its first-round NCAA tournament game against the University of Tennessee.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] On March 13, 2009, AU's men's basketball team repeated as Patriot League Champion by defeating Holy Cross 73–57, earning an automatic bid to the NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] They ultimately lost to Villanova University in the first round on March 19, 2009, with a final score of 80–67.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Notable university alumni, faculty, and affiliates include eight foreign heads of state; over 30 U.S. senators and representatives; two governors; a lieutenant governor; multiple U.S.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/american-university] Cabinet members; two Nobel laureates; two Pulitzer Prize winners; an Academy Award recipient; many Fulbright Scholars; more than 30 ambassadors; and prominent global finance leaders.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/baking-chocolate] Modern manufactured baking chocolate is typically formed from chocolate liquor formed into bars or chocolate chips.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/baking-chocolate] Baking chocolate may be of a lower quality compared to other types of chocolate, and may have part of the cocoa butter replaced with other fats that do not require tempering.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/baking-chocolate] This type of baking chocolate may be easier to handle compared to those that have not had their cocoa butter content lowered.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/baking-chocolate] It is typically prepared in unsweetened, bittersweet, semisweet and sweet varieties, depending on the amount of added sugar.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/baking-chocolate] Recipes that include unsweetened baking chocolate typically use a significant amount of sugar.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/baking-chocolate] Bittersweet baking chocolate must contain 35 percent chocolate liquor or higher.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/baking-chocolate] Most baking chocolates have at least a 50% cocoa content, with the remaining content usually being mostly sugar.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/baking-chocolate] Sweet varieties may be referred to as "sweet baking chocolate" or "sweet chocolate".
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/baking-chocolate] Sweet baking chocolate contains more sugar than bittersweet and semisweet varieties, and semisweet varieties contain more sugar than bittersweet varieties.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/baking-chocolate] Sweet and semisweet baking chocolate is prepared with a chocolate liquor content between 15 and 35 percent.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/baking-chocolate] The table below denotes the four primary varieties of baking chocolate.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/baking-chocolate] Manufacturers of baking chocolate include Baker's Chocolate, Callebaut, Fazer, Ghirardelli, Guittard, The Hershey Company, Lindt, Menier, and Valrhona.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/bananas] The film was criticized by Dole for containing "patent falsehoods".
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/bananas] After a screening at the Los Angeles Film Festival in June 2009, Gertten was sued for defamation by Dole on 8 July.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/bananas] The lawsuit was preceded by threats of legal action from Dole aimed against the LA Film Festival, which resulted in sponsors pulling support and the film being removed from competition.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/bananas] Dole dropped their lawsuit against Fredrik Gertten and *Bananas!** on 15 October 2009.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/bananas] In September 2009, the Swedish parliament members Mats Johansson (M) and Luciano Astudillo (S) took the initiative of displaying the movie in the Parliament of Sweden, this being its premiere in Sweden.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/bananas] In late 2010 a court in Los Angeles decided in favor of the movie crew, making it possible to release the film in the US.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/bananas] A judge awarded the filmmakers nearly $200,000 in fees and costs.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/bananas] In 2011, Gertten directed the film *Big Boys Gone Bananas!** about how the company was sued by Dole.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] Barry Callebaut's customers include multinational and national branded consumer goods manufacturers and artisanal users of chocolate (chocolatiers, pastry chefs, bakeries, and caterers).
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] Cacao Barry was founded in Hardricourt, France, by Charles Barry, an Englishman with an interest for exploring Africa in 1842.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] During Barry's travels to Africa, he came in contact with cocoa beans, a major component in the production of chocolate, which the company began producing in 1911.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In 1952, Cacao Barry began to produce gourmet chocolate.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In 1992, the holding company Société Centrale d'Investissement (SCI) gained control of Cacao Barry and transferred 49% of its capital to Compagnie Nationale à Portefeuille (CNP), an investment fund in financier Albert Frère's group.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] SCI's management approach favoured greater penetration of the British market, with the consequent opening of a production site in the United Kingdom.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] Callebaut was a Belgian company, founded by Eugenius Callebaut as a brewery in Wieze in 1850.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] The brewery began producing chocolate bars in 1911 under Octaaf Callebaut and soon switched entirely to chocolate production.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] They began producing couverture chocolate in 1925.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In the 1950s, Callebaut, which was still a family-run business, began exporting its products to other European as well as North American markets, leveraging the fact that Belgian chocolate had earned an excellent reputation for its quality.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In 1981, Interfood, a subsidiary of Tobler-Suchard, bought the company.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In 1983, Klaus Jacobs acquired full control of Interfood, the holding company that controlled Callebaut, and became an international confectionery leader.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] After a series of acquisitions in the industry, the company merged with the US company Kraft in 1987, creating Kraft Jacobs Suchard.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] Bernard Callebaut, heir of the founding family, moved to Calgary, Canada, in 1982, where he opened a chocolate factory named Chocolaterie Bernard Callebaut.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] Cacao Barry and Callebaut merged in 1996 to form Barry Callebaut.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In 1998, the company was listed on the SIX Swiss Exchange.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] From a business standpoint, the new Franco-Belgian confectionery company continued to grow, with Jacobs Suchard assigning it the management of Van Houten, the Dutch chocolate and cocoa powder maker founded in 1815 in Amsterdam, which Suchard had acquired in 1986.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In 1999, the company acquired the US-based confectionery Van Leer Chocolate and, the following year, it purchased the Swiss Carma-Pfister AG.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In 2002, it acquired the German company Stollwerck for $225 million, thereby taking over the 17 brands under its control, including Sarotti.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In 2007, Barry Callebaut signed an agreement with fellow Swiss brand Nestlé to supply it with 43,000 tonnes of chocolate products per year.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] Before the year was out, it had acquired KL Kepong Cocoa Products Sdn Bhd in Port Klang, Malaysia.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In 2009, Barry Callebaut bought the Spanish chocolate producer Chocovic S.A.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] These international acquisitions took place in the space of a few years, leading CEO Patrick G.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] De Maeseneire to announce, "We don't want to be a European company only, we want to be a global company".
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] Two years later, the company transfered its Stollwerck division to the Belgian Baronie Group, disposing of most of its retail operations in European markets.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In 2017, Barry Callebaut acquired D'Orsogna Dolciaria, an Italian company specializing in the production of amaretto biscuits, confectionery decorations, and similar products.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] Barry Callebaut operates the largest chocolate factory in the world, located in the Belgian town of Wieze.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] Around 350,000 tons of chocolate are produced there every year.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In 2005, Barry Callebaut introduced a "healthy" chocolate product called ACTICOA, which contains higher levels of polyphenol antioxidants (cocoa flavanols) than any other chocolate; some evidence indicates these flavanols have particular health benefits.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In 2017, Barry Callebaut launched a new type of chocolate, ruby, named after its reddish-pink colour, which is due to the colour of the cocoa beans from which it is made.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In 2018, Nestlé Japan Ltd. launched the ruby chocolate-based Ruby Sublime KitKat, becoming the first global brand to use the pink chocolate formula.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] The product was also launched the same year in the UK.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In 2022, Barry Callebaut announced the "second generation of chocolate", which, according to the company, has 50 percent less sugar than most other chocolates.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In addition, the dark chocolate consists of only two ingredients and the milk chocolate of only three.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] From 2015 to 2021, Antoine Bernard de Saint-Affrique was CEO of the company, after which Peter Boone took over the position, holding it until 2023, when it went to Peter Feld.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] As of May 2024, the company was 30.1% owned by the Zurich-based Jacobs Holding, 5% by Renata Jacobs, 3.1% by BlackRock, and 6.5% by UBS.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] On 13 September 2017 NGO Mighty Earth released a report documenting findings that Barry Callebaut purchases cocoa grown illegally in national parks and other protected forests in the Ivory Coast.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] The report accused Barry Callebaut of endangering the forest habitats of chimpanzees, elephants and other wildlife populations by purchasing cocoa linked to deforestation.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] As a result of cocoa production, 7 of the 23 Ivorian protected areas have been almost entirely converted to cocoa.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] Barry Callebaut was notified of the findings of Mighty Earth's investigation and did not deny that the company sourced its cocoa from protected areas in the Ivory Coast.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] A follow-on report by Mighty Earth dated 7 December 2018 indicated little to no progress had been made in the year since Barry Callebaut and other signatories had committed to the Cocoa and Forests Initiative.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] The chocolate industry, including Barry Callebaut, signed the Harkin-Engel Protocol in September 2001.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] This protocol contains measures that were intended to end the worst forms of child labor and slavery in the cocoa industry by 2008.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] A report by ARD in 2010 concluded that large companies such as Mars Incorporated, but also Barry Callebaut and Nestlé still "at least tolerate" child slavery.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] An evaluation by Tulane University in 2011 found that not a single one of the six measures mentioned in the Harkin-Engel Protocol had been fully implemented.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In 2021, Barry Callebaut was named in a class action lawsuit filed by eight former child slaves from Mali who alleged that the company aided and abetted their enslavement on cocoa plantations in Ivory Coast.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In 2022, the "Chocolate Scorecard", a comparative overview of production conditions led by Australian universities, attested that the company was "beginning to establish good policies" regarding child labor.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In the overall assessment of the environmental and social criteria, however, Callebaut was only ranked 24th out of 35 companies.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] The authors viewed the company's performance in areas such as transparency, livelihoods, agroforestry and, in particular, agrochemical management as particularly critical.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] On 27 June 2022 Salmonella contamination was detected in a batch of chocolates at the Wieze, Belgium plant halting production.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] A shipment of the ingredient lecithin was identified as the source.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] No salmonella was detected at the Hungarian manufacturer's plant.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] The contamination was traced back to a single contaminated tanker delivery.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] Production was resumed gradually after 8 August, going back to full capacity by 20 October 2022 after the factory facilities were cleaned.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/barry-callebaut] In January 2024 Barry Callebaut was added to the list of International Sponsors of War for continuing to operate 3 factories in Russia, and having their products used in dry rations of the Russian army.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Child labour is a recurring issue in cocoa production.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Ivory Coast and Ghana together produce nearly 60% of the world's cocoa each year.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] During the 2018/19 cocoa-growing season, research commissioned by the U.S.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Department of Labor was conducted by NORC at the University of Chicago in these two countries and found that 1.48 million children are engaged in hazardous work on cocoa farms including working with sharp tools and agricultural chemicals and carrying heavy loads.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The number of children is significant, representing 43 percent of all children living in agricultural households in cocoa-growing areas.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] During the same period cocoa production in Ivory Coast and Ghana increased 62 percent while the prevalence of child labour in cocoa production among all agricultural households increased by 14 percentage points.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Attention on this subject has focused on West Africa, which collectively supplies 69% of the world's cocoa, and Côte d'Ivoire, supplying 35%, in particular.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The 2016 Global Estimates of Child Labor indicate that one-fifth of all African children are involved in child labour.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Nine percent of African children are in hazardous work.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] It is estimated that more than 1.8 million children in West Africa are involved in growing cocoa.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] According to the NORC study, methodological differences between the 2018/9 survey and earlier ones, together with errors in the administration of the 2013/4 survey have made it challenging to document changes in the number of children engaged in child labour over the past five years.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] A major study of the issue, published in *Fortune* magazine in the U.S. in March 2016, concluded that approximately 2.1 million children in West Africa "still do the dangerous and physically taxing work of harvesting cocoa".
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The report was doubtful as to whether the situation can be improved significantly.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In 2001, the report *A Taste of Slavery: How Your Chocolate May be Tainted* won a George Polk Award.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In it were claims that traffickers promised paid work, housing, and education to children who were forced to labour and undergo severe abuse, that some children were held forcibly on farms and worked up to 100 hours per week, and that attempted escapees were beaten.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] A small observational study, published in 2005 and financed by USAID, examines the many health hazards of cocoa production in western Ghana.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In 2006, a study showed many children working on small farms in Côte d'Ivoire, often on family farms.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Over 11,000 people working on small Ivorian cocoa farms were surveyed.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In 2008, in a report featuring responses from Cargill and Hershey's, *Fortune* magazine reported that "little progress has been made", and in June 2009, the OECD released a position paper on child labour on West African Cocoa Farms, and launched a website on its Regional Cocoa Initiative.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] A major report released in 2015 by the Payson Center for International Development of Tulane University, funded by the United States Department of Labor, reported a 51% increase in the number of child workers (1.4 million) in the cocoa industry in 2013–14, compared to 2008–09.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The report estimated that over 1.4 million children ages 5 years old to 11 years old were working in agriculture in cocoa-growing areas, approximately 800,000 of them engaged in hazardous work, including working with agricultural chemicals, carrying heavy loads, and working with sharp tools.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] A study of the issue, published in *Fortune* magazine in the U.S. in March 2016, concluded that approximately 2.1 million children in West Africa "still do the dangerous and physically taxing work of harvesting cocoa".
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Getting that other 90% won't be easy. ...
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] I think child labour cannot be just the responsibility of industry to solve.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] I think it's the proverbial all-hands-on-deck: government, humane society, the private sector.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Reported in 2018, a three-year pilot program – conducted by Nestlé through the International Cocoa Initiative with 26,000 farmers mostly located in Côte d'Ivoire – observed a 51% decrease in the number of children doing hazardous jobs in cocoa farming.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] A separate sub-study conducted by NORC and commissioned by the World Cocoa Foundation in 2019, provides detailed results which demonstrate that hazardous child labour has been reduced by one-third in communities where company programs are in place.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The US Department of Labor formed the Child Labor Cocoa Coordinating Group as a public-private partnership with the governments of Ghana and Côte d'Ivoire to address child labour practices in the cocoa industry.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The International Cocoa Initiative involving major cocoa manufacturers established the Child Labour Monitoring and Remediation System intended to monitor thousands of farms in Ghana and Côte d'Ivoire for child labour conditions.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Despite these efforts, goals to reduce child labour in West Africa by 70% before 2020 are slowed by persistent poverty, absence of schools, expansion of cocoa farmland, and increased demand for coco.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] A report later that year by *New Food Economy* stated that the Child Labour Monitoring and Remediation Systems implemented by the International Cocoa Initiative and its partners has been useful, but "they are currently reaching less than 20 percent of the over two million children impacted".
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] According to the 2018 edition of the Cocoa Barometer, a biennial report examining the economics of cocoa that's published by a consortium of nonprofits, the current farmer income is $.78.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Class action lawsuits in the US against companies in the cocoa industry have not achieved much success.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In 2015, lawsuits against Mars, Nestlé, and Hershey's alleged that their products' packaging failed to disclose that production may involve child slave labour.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] All were dismissed in 2016, although the plaintiffs filed an appeal.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The company said it had spent $5.5 million on the problem in 2016.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Nestlé had also published a report in 2017 on child labour in the cocoa supply chain, Tackling Child Labour, with additional specifics as to their "approach to addressing this significant, complex and sensitive challenge".
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Income from the cocoa industry for small cocoa farmers is not stable because when the market price of cocoa is low, the price paid to each link in the industry decreases and cocoa farmers who produce raw products get very little in the chain.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] To keep the cost of cocoa low, cocoa farmers seek the cheapest labour to make a profit.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In Africa, a cocoa labourer can only make less than 2 dollars per day, which is below the poverty line.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Child labourers between the ages of 12 and 15 in the cocoa industry work as much as an adult labourer, but they are paid less than adults.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Children in cocoa growing areas face the realities of rural poverty (scarcity of land, food insecurity, lack of education infrastructure, access to potable water, poor health services, etc.).
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The regular practice of children working on cocoa farms is often a natural way of life for cocoa farmers who, for a variety of reasons, want to train their children and at the same time use them to reduce labour costs on the family's farm.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Work done that is not detrimental to children's health, development or schooling is beneficial because it allows children to develop skills, gain experience and prepare them for future positions; these are not considered child labour or abuse.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The forms of child labour related to cocoa production includes parents putting their children to work and keeping them out of school to reduce labour cost on family farms.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Most children who work on cocoa farms do so within their family structure.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] However, this does not mean they are not exposed to hazards, and, beyond these situations, illegal and exploitative practices also exist.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Studies suggest that in Ghana and Cote d’Ivoire's cocoa sector roughly 1% of children in child labour could be in, or at risk of, forced labour.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The United Nations declared 2021 as the International Year for the Elimination of Child Labour, and declared 5 September to be "Labour Day".
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] A 2000 BBC documentary described child slavery on commercial cocoa farms in Côte d'Ivoire.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The documentary featured Kevin Bales, renowned author and professor, who later became the founding board member of the International Cocoa Initiative, a Geneva-based nonprofit funded by major chocolate makers that focuses on addressing child labour in cocoa production in West Africa.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In 2001, the United States Department of State estimated there were 15,000 child slaves in cocoa, cotton, and coffee farms in Côte d'Ivoire, and the Chocolate Manufacturers Association acknowledged that children were used in the cocoa harvest of cocoa.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Malian migrants have long worked on cocoa farms in Côte d'Ivoire, but in 2000 cocoa prices had dropped to a 10-year low and some farmers stopped paying their employees.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The Malian counsel had to rescue boys who had not been paid for five years and who were beaten if they tried to run away.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Malian officials believed that 15,000 children, some as young as 11 years old, were working in Côte d'Ivoire in 2001.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] These children were often from poor families or the slums and were sold for "just a few dollars" to work in other countries.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Parents were told the children would find work and send money home, but once the children left home, they often worked in conditions resembling slavery.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In other cases, children begging for food were lured from bus stations and sold as slaves.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In 2002, Côte d'Ivoire had 12,000 children with no relatives nearby, which suggested they were trafficked, likely from neighboring Mali, Burkina Faso and Togo.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] According to a 2009 snowball sampling study, the majority of those with childhood cocoa labour experience were trafficked (75% from Burkina Faso and 63% from Mali).
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The majority of those who were trafficked had no interaction with police, and only 0.5% had any contact from institutions that provided social services.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Burkina Faso and Togo are rated at Tier 2 in part due to trafficking for cocoa production.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] By 2020, West African nations Ghana and Côte d'Ivoire were upgraded to Tier 2 in the 2020 US State Department's TIP Report in part for their respective progress to curb child labour abuses in the cocoa sector.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In 2001, due to pressure applied by the US Congress and potential US and United Kingdom boycotts, the chocolate manufacturers promised to start eliminating forced child labour.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In 2012, Ferrero promised that they will end cocoa slavery by 2020.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Department of Labor issued a report on labour conditions around the world in which a *List of Goods Produced by Child Labor or Forced Labor* mentioned five countries where the cocoa industry used child labour, and two countries where the cocoa industry used child labour and forced labour.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] News reports as recently as 2018, indicate that "most child slaves on cocoa farms (Cote d’Ivoire and Ghana) come from Mali and Burkina Faso, two of the poorest nations on Earth.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The children, some as young as ten, are sent by their families or trafficked by agents with the promise of money.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In 2021, several companies were named in a class action lawsuit filed by eight former children from Mali who alleged that the companies aided and abetted their enslavement on cocoa plantations in Cote d’Ivoire.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The suit accused Barry Callebaut, Cargill, The Hershey Company, Mars, Mondelez, Nestlé, and Olam International, of knowingly engaging in forced labour, and the plaintiffs sought damages for unjust enrichment, negligent supervision, and intentional infliction of emotional distress.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In June 2020, the United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit unanimously found that state product labeling laws did not require Nestlé, Mars Inc., or the Hershey Company to disclose on chocolate wrappers if the ingredients used were produced by forced child labor.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The households face the realities of rural poverty such as a scarcity of land, food insecurity, limited access to quality education, lack of access to drinking water and inadequate health services.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In Ghana, the cocoa industry began in the late 19th century and in Côte d'Ivoire it began in the early 20th century.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Ghana became the largest cocoa producer in the world in 1910.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] By 1980 Côte d'Ivoire overtook Ghana as the biggest producer.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In both countries, the majority of farms are small and family-owned.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Family members, including children, are often expected to work on the farms.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In the 2018–2019 growing year (which runs October through September), 4.78 hundred thousand tonnes of cocoa beans were produced.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] African nations produced 2.45 million tonnes (69%), Asia and Oceania 0.61 million tonnes (17%) and the Americas 0.48 million tonnes (14%).
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Two African nations, Côte d'Ivoire and Ghana, produce more than half of the world's cocoa, with 1.23 and 0.73 million tonnes respectively (35% and 21%, respectively).
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Different metrics are used for chocolate consumption.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The Netherlands has the highest monetary amount of cocoa bean imports (US$2.1 billion); it is also one of the main ports into Europe.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The US has highest amount of cocoa powder imports ($220 million); the US has a large amount of cocoa complementary products.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The UK has the highest amount of retail chocolate ($1.3 billion) and is one of the biggest chocolate consumption per capita markets.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Because of the delicate nature of the cocoa tree species, cocoa trees are treated with pesticides and fungicides.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Cocoa harvest is not restricted to one period per year and occurs over a period of several months to the whole year.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Pods are harvested at multiple times during the harvest season because they do not all ripen at once.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Pod ripening is judged by pod color, and ripe pods are harvested from the trunk and branches of the cocoa tree with a curved knife on a long pole.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The pods are opened and wet beans are removed.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Wet beans are transported to a facility so they can be fermented and dried.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Many of these tasks could be hazardous when performed by children, according to the ILO.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Mixing and applying chemicals can be hazardous due to pesticide contamination, especially because no protective clothing is worn during application.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Clearing vegetation and harvesting pods can be hazardous because these tasks are often done using machetes, which can cause lacerations.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] This skill is part of normal development in children 15 to 17 years old, but is a higher risk in younger children.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Many have wounds on their legs where they have cut themselves.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Department of Labour indicates that in 2005, 92 percent of children between the ages of 5 and 15 are involved in heavy load carrying work in the cocoa industry, which can cause open wounds.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Transport of the wet beans can also be hazardous due to long transport distances and heavy loads; hernias and physical injuries can occur.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The International Cocoa Initiative upholds the International Conventions that promote child rights and that outlaw child labour practices, as well as the relevant supporting national laws.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Not all work done by children is classified as child labour.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] For instance, children carrying out light, non-hazardous tasks on the family farm for a limited period of time, under supervision, and without compromising their schooling, is considered as acceptable child work.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] This type of work is often necessary for the welfare of many families in West African rural societies.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] It also contributes to children's development, providing them with skills and experience that help them prepare for their adult farming life.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] By contrast, activities such as carrying heavy loads or using chemicals are considered as "unacceptable forms of child labour", because they are physically dangerous for children.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Child trafficking and any work undertaken by children in bonded labour are extreme and criminal forms of child exploitation.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In 2019, the International Cocoa Initiative investigated the prevalence of child labour in the cocoa industry.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] It found 7,319 children identified as involved in one or more hazardous tasks.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In the 2000s, some chocolate producers began to engage in fair trade initiatives, to address concerns about the marginalization of cocoa labourers in developing countries.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Traditionally, Africa and other developing countries received low prices for their exported commodities such as cocoa, which caused poverty to abound.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Fairtrade seeks to establish a system of direct trade from developing countries to counteract this unfair system.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] One solution for fair labour practices is for farmers to become part of an agricultural cooperative.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Cooperatives pay farmers a fair price for their cocoa so farmers have enough money for food, clothes, and school fees.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] One of the main tenets of fair trade is that farmers receive a fair price, but this does not mean that the larger amount of money paid for fair trade cocoa goes directly to the farmers.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The effectiveness of fair trade has been questioned.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In a 2014 article, *The Economist* stated that workers on fair trade farms have a lower standard of living than on similar farms outside the fair trade system.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] 2019 research from the International Cocoa Initiative found a strong correlation between higher quality education and lower prevalence of child labour.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] ICI found that in the communities with the highest quality of education score, child labour prevalence stood at 10%, or 66% lower than in the communities with the lowest quality of education score.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] To combat child slavery in cocoa production, in 2001 US Representative Eliot Engel introduced a legislative amendment to fund the development of a "no child slavery" label for chocolate products sold in the United States.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Senator Tom Harkin proposed an addition to an agriculture bill to label qualified chocolate and cocoa products as "slave free".
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] It was approved in the House of Representatives by a vote of 291–115, but before it went to the Senate the chocolate makers hired former senators George Mitchell and Bob Dole to lobby against it, and it did not go to a vote.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Instead, the chocolate manufacturers reached agreement with the Congressmen to create the Harkin–Engel Protocol to remove child forced labour from the industry by July 2005.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The chocolate makers were to create programs in West Africa to make Africans aware of the consequences of child labour, keeping their children from an education, and child trafficking.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The primary incentive for the companies' voluntary participation would be the addition of a "slave free" label.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The 2005 deadline was not met, and all parties agreed to a three-year extension of the Protocol.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] This extension allowed the cocoa industry more time to implement the Protocol including creating a certification system to address the worst forms of child labour for half of the growing areas in Côte d'Ivoire and Ghana.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] By 2008, the industry had collected data from over half of the areas, as required, but they did not have proper independent verification.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] In June 2008, the Protocol was extended until the end of 2010.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] At that time, the industry was required to have full certifications with independent verifications.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The European Union passed a resolution in 2012 to fully implement the Harkin–Engel Protocol and fight child labour in cocoa production.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The resolution was criticized by the International Labor Rights Forum for having no legally binding measures and two major chocolate manufacturers claimed they were addressing the problem.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] The industry's pledge to reduce child labour in Cote d’Ivoire and Ghana by 70%, as per the Framework of Action in 2010, had not been met as of late 2015; the deadline was again extended, to 2020.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] According to the 2022 Chocolate Scorecard seven of the major chocolate companies are 'leading the industry' on child labour and a further seventeen companies are 'starting to implement good policies'.
[src:child-labour-in-cocoa-production/child-labour-in-cocoa-production] Companies who claimed to be addressing child labour were asked to provide evidence for this and were scored according to whether their reports were external or internal, whether just numbers or actual impact was measured, and how recently the study was undertaken.
